Loan Data Exploration¶

by Medha Vaish¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many other

The structure of your dataset¶

The dataset has 81 features and 113937 enteries. We now need to explore only those variables which are needed for our analysis

The main feature(s) of interest in the dataset¶

Main feature of interest here is to analyse what guides the APR(Annual Percentage rate for a loan) of borrower for a loan

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of APR looks multimodal. A small peak centered at 0.1, a large peak centered at 0.2. There is also a small peak centered 0.3. Additionally, there is a very shape peak between 0.35 and 0.36. Only very few loans have APR greater than 0.43.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Stated monthly income was skewed with only 0.28% values greater than 30,000. The largest value was quite high ie 17,50,002. We ignored values > 30k as these can be considered as outliers

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section,I'll investigate relationships between pairs of variables in my data.

First of all lets divide the variables into numerical variables and categorical variables

Numerical= [LoanOriginalAmount, BorrowerAPR, StatedMonthlyIncome, BorrowerRate,ProsperScore]

Categorical = [Term,ProsperRating (Alpha), EmploymentStatus, Occupation,BorrowerState]

In [20]:
#Finding relation between numerical values
fig, ax= plt.subplots(4, figsize=(10,15))
# subplot 1: BorrowerAPR vs LoanOriginalAmount
sb.regplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'LoanOriginalAmount', y = 'BorrowerAPR', ax=ax[0],x_jitter= 0.1, truncate=False, scatter_kws={'alpha':1/20})

# subplot 2: BorrowerAPR vs StatedMonthlyIncome
sb.regplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'StatedMonthlyIncome', y = 'BorrowerAPR', ax=ax[1], x_jitter=0.1, truncate=False,scatter_kws={'alpha':1/20})

# subplot 3: BorrowerAPR  vs BorrowerRate
sb.regplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'BorrowerRate', y = 'BorrowerAPR', ax=ax[2])

#subplot 4: BorrowerAPR vs ProsperScore
sb.regplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'ProsperScore', y = 'BorrowerAPR', ax=ax[3], x_jitter=0.1,scatter_kws={'alpha':1/20});

A positive correlation seen between APR and borrower rate Borrower APR decreases with increasing Loan amount For low prosper score the Borrower APR is high and for high prosper score the borrower APR is low

In [21]:
#Finding relations between categorical values
fig, ax= plt.subplots(3, figsize=(10,12))
# subplot 1: Prosper rating vs term
PR_order = ['AA','A', 'B','C','D','E','HR']
# Returns the types for PR_order with the categories and orderedness
vclasses1 = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=PR_order)
# Use pandas.astype() to convert the "vordered" column from a plain object type into an ordered categorical type 
sub_loan['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = sub_loan['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(vclasses1)
sb.countplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', hue = 'Term', palette = 'Reds', ax=ax[0])

# subplot 2: employment status vs term
sb.countplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'EmploymentStatus', hue = 'Term', palette = 'Blues', ax=ax[1])

# subplot 3: Prosper rating vs employment status

sb.countplot(data = sub_loan, x = 'EmploymentStatus', hue = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', palette = 'Greens', ax=ax[2])
plt.xticks(rotation=10);
#leaving occupation and state because of large number of value counts

Most of the loans are for 36 months term despite the prosper rating. Most of the loans are taken by employed and full time workers with term of 36 months The most common rating for employed and self employed is C. For full time the most common rating is A

In [23]:
#correlation plot between the numerical variables
v_num = ['LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerAPR', 'StatedMonthlyIncome','BorrowerRate','ProsperScore']
sb.heatmap(sub_loan[v_num].corr(method='pearson'), annot=True, linewidth= 0.5, cmap='YlGnBu', center=0,fmt = '.3f');

We see a strong positive correlation between Borrower APR and borrower rate, which is quite obvious

A negative correlation of 0.323 is observed between Borrower APR and Loan Original Amount, which shows tha as the loan amount increases the APR decreases

A negative correlation of 0.178 is observed between Borrower APR and Stated Monthly Income, which shows that as the monthly income increases the APR decreases. We can also see that there is positive correlation between loan original amount and monthly income

Prosper score is strongly negatively correlated with Borrower APR, ie rating increases with decrease in borrower APR

Variation in borrower APR decreases as the term of loan is increasing. Not much difference can be obsereved

Borrower APR vs Employment Status¶

For not employed there is a bulge at higher APR. We can say they have higher APR. There is a bulge at lowe APr values for others who are employed, self employed, part time or full time and retired. Not much can be observed for others

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The loan original amount is positively correlated with the stated monthly income. Positive correlation between prosper score and loan amount as well as prosper score and stated monthly income which can be because of the fact that the person with more income has better prosper score
